SIMPLE: squint
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Squint
<hw>Squint</hw> <pr>(skw⟦icr⟧nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D.
<ets>schuinte</ets> a slope, <ets>schuin</ets>, <ets>schuinsch</ets>,
sloping, oblique, <ets>schuins</ets> slopingly. Cf. <er>Askant</er>,
<er>Askance</er>, <er>Asquint</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Looking
obliquely.</def> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <fld>(Med.)</fld>,
<def>not having the optic axes coincident; -- said of the eyes. See
<er>Squint</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>Fig.:</mark> <def>Looking askance.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Squint</xex> suspicion.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Squint
<hw>Squint</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Squinted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Squinting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To see or look
obliquely, asquint, or awry, or with a furtive glance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some can <qex>squint</qex> when they will.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To have the axes of the eyes not
coincident; to be cross-eyed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deviate from a true line; to run
obliquely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To have an indirect bearing, reference, or
implication; to have an allusion to, or inclination towards,
something.</def></p>

<p><q>Yet if the following sentence means anything, it is a
<qex>squinting</qex> toward hypnotism.</q> <rj><qau>The
Forum.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To look with the eyes partly closed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Squint
<hw>Squint</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn to an oblique
position; to direct obliquely; <as>as, to <ex>squint</ex> an
eye</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to look with noncoincident optic
axes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . <qex>squints</qex> the eye, and makes the harelid.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squint</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Squint
<hw>Squint</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or habit of
squinting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A want of coincidence of the axes
of the eyes; strabismus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Same as
<er>Hagioscope</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Squinter</ent>⟦br⟧
